.venv/
generated/
__pycache__/
*.pyc
examples/**/*.test
examples/tasks-api/tasks-api
bin/
*.egg-info/
.pytest_cache/

# local run artifacts (distillation farm + raw traces)
farm/
traces/
# logs/* — NOT logs/. Git cannot re-include a file whose parent DIRECTORY is
# excluded, so with `logs/` the negation below is dead text that silently does
# nothing. Excluding the CONTENTS instead leaves the directory visible, which is
# what makes the exception work. (Found the way everything else was found today:
# the commit refused the file and I read the error instead of retrying it.)
logs/*

# ...except the predictions. These are not run artifacts, they are the method:
# each one is a claim written down BEFORE its measurement, including the outcome
# that would refute it. That ordering is the only thing separating "I predicted
# this" from "I explained this afterwards", and it is worth exactly as much as it
# is verifiable. Today it nearly wasn't: I stamped these files with times I never
# read off a clock, drifting an hour into the future, and the ordering was only
# recoverable because GIT held the real times. The timekeeper should hold the
# record too. Raw logs stay ignored — they are regenerable; a prediction is not.
!logs/PREDICTION-*.txt
